# Mobile Editor Context

The "mobile editor" refers to the `/editor` route when viewed on a mobile device.

## Key Details

- Route: `/editor` and `/editor/:doctype` (see `src/App.tsx`)
- Mobile detection: use the `useIsMobile` hook from `@/hooks/useIsMobile` (breakpoint: 600px)
- Source files live under `src/pages/Editor/`

## Mobile-Specific Components

- `MobileHeader` (`src/pages/Editor/components/MobileHeader/`) — condensed gradient header with home, undo/redo, comment, present, share, more icons
- `MobileActionBar` (`src/pages/Editor/components/MobileActionBar/`) — bottom action bar with Ask Canva, Replace, Magic BG, Color, Duration, Done
- `MobileContextToolbar` (`src/pages/Editor/components/MobileContextToolbar/`) — floating toolbar shown above selected element (replace + more)

## Behaviour on Mobile

- The primary sidebar (`PrimaryNav`) is hidden on mobile (handled in `App.tsx`).
- `NavTabs` is hidden when inside the editor on mobile (handled in `App.tsx`).
- The contextual nav (`ContextualNav`) is also hidden on mobile.
- The desktop `Header`, `EditorToolbar`, `ObjectPanel`, `EditPanel`, and `EditorFooter` are all hidden on mobile.
- Instead, the mobile editor renders: `MobileHeader`, full-width canvas, `PageNavigator` (static, not fixed), `MobileActionBar`, and `MobileContextToolbar` (when an element is selected).
- Each doctype component (`PresentationDoctype`, `DocumentDoctype`, etc.) accepts an `isMobile` prop to hide the `EditorFooter`.

## Guidelines

- Always test editor changes against the mobile viewport (390×844, or any width < 600px).
- Prefer responsive, touch-friendly controls over desktop-only interactions (e.g. hover menus).
- Reuse existing editor components from `src/pages/Editor/components/` where possible.
- The mobile layout is a separate render branch in `Editor/index.tsx` (not CSS-only responsive).
